import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


# Data Preparation
data['CRASH TIME'] = pd.to_datetime(data['CRASH TIME'])
data['TIME OF DAY'] = data['CRASH TIME'].dt.hour
data['SEVERITY'] = data['SEVERITY'].astype(float)

# Time of Day Analysis
time_of_day_collisions = data['TIME OF DAY'].value_counts().sort_index()

# Severity Analysis
time_of_day_severity = data.groupby('TIME OF DAY')['SEVERITY'].mean()

# Correlation Analysis
correlation = data['TIME OF DAY'].corr(data['SEVERITY'])

# Data Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

# Plot the average severity by time of day
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
time_of_day_severity.plot(kind='line')
plt.title('Average Severity by Time of Day')
plt.xlabel('Time of Day')
plt.ylabel('Average Severity')

plt.tight_layout()

# Show the correlation between time of day and severity
print(f'Correlation between Time of Day and Severity: {correlation}')

# Display the plots
plt.show()

import pandas as pd

# Load your data from the uploaded CSV file, handling bad lines
data = pd.read_csv("C:\\Users\\nredd\\OneDrive\\Documents\\2nd sem\\AIT580\\Project sample\\collision_data_new.csv", encoding='utf-8')

# Convert 'CRASH.TIME' to datetime format
data['CRASH TIME'] = pd.to_datetime(data['CRASH TIME'], format='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S').dt.time

# Fill missing values in each column with the mode
for column in data.columns:
    mode_value = data[column].mode()[0]
    data[column].fillna(mode_value, inplace=True)

# Analyze the relationship between time of day and collisions
time_of_day_counts = data['CRASH TIME'].apply(lambda x: x.hour).value_counts().sort_index()
severity_by_time = data.groupby(data['CRASH TIME'].apply(lambda x: x.hour))['SEVERITY'].mean()

# Display the results
print("Number of collisions by time of day:")
print(time_of_day_counts)

print("\nAverage severity by time of day:")
print(severity_by_time)

# Check the unique values in the contributing factors columns
import seaborn as sns

contributing_factors_columns = [
    'CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 1',
    'CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 2',
    'CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 3',
    'CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 4',
    'CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 5'
]

all_contributing_factors = set()

for column in contributing_factors_columns:
    all_contributing_factors.update(data[column].unique())

# Display the unique contributing factors
#print("Unique Contributing Factors:\n", all_contributing_factors)

# Visualize the most common contributing factors
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
top_contributing_factors = data[contributing_factors_columns].stack().value_counts().nlargest(10)
sns.barplot(x=top_contributing_factors.values, y=top_contributing_factors.index, palette='viridis')
plt.title('Top 10 Contributing Factors to Motor Vehicle Collisions')
plt.xlabel('Number of Collisions')
plt.ylabel('Contributing Factors')
plt.show()
In [32]:
    # Drop rows with missing values in relevant columns
    data = data.dropna(subset=['CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 1', 'BOROUGH'])

    # Group by borough and contributing factor, and calculate the count
    grouped_data = data.groupby(['BOROUGH', 'CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 1']).size().reset_index(name='COUNT')

    # Pivot the data to create a heatmap-friendly format
    heatmap_data = grouped_data.pivot(index='CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 1', columns='BOROUGH', values='COUNT').fillna(0)

    # Plot a heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    sns.heatmap(heatmap_data, cmap='Blues', annot=True, fmt='.0f', linewidths=.5)
    plt.title('Motor Vehicle Collisions by Contributing Factor and Borough')
    plt.xlabel('Borough')
    plt.ylabel('Contributing Factor')
    plt.show()

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Select relevant features and target variable
features = ['TIME OF DAY', 'CONTRIBUTING FACTOR VEHICLE 1', 'BOROUGH']
target = 'SEVERITY'

# Encode categorical variables
data_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data[features + [target]])

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(data_encoded.drop(target, axis=1), data_encoded[target], test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Train a Decision Tree classifier
classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = classifier.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the classifier
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
classification_rep = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(classification_rep)
